{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5e647b8-b543-44df-986a-678ce91de360","content":"For waits/blocks under load, collect a **Thread Time trace** (wall-clock, includes blocked/waiting time) rather than a CPU-only trace.\n\n**PerfView command:**\n\n```\nPerfView /threadTime /nogui /accepteula /zip /merge /maxCollectSec:30 collect\n```\n\n**Key arguments explained:**\n\n| Flag | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `/threadTime` | Enables context-switch & ready-thread events so you see **blocked time** (locks, I/O, async awaits), not just CPU |\n| `/maxCollectSec:30` | Limits collection to 30s — adjust to cover your repro window |\n| `/zip /merge` | Produces a single portable `.etl.zip` |\n| `/nogui` | Headless — safe for production servers |\n\n**Analysis:** Open the resulting file in PerfView → **Thread Time Stacks** → filter to your process. Look for `BLOCKED_TIME` frames to identify lock contention, synchronous I/O, or thread-pool starvation.\n\n**Tip:** If you also suspect thread-pool starvation, add `/ClrEvents=ThreadPool` to capture thread-pool worker injection events.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"66c5f6e0-ce36-49f5-bfcc-ac1661318e9c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about performance tracing for an ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) app on Windows Server under load, specifically about capturing waits/blocks using PerfView.","outputTokens":339,"requestId":"9437:180180:182169D:1B5CDEB:69E81C81"},"id":"1ae621ad-4d79-4b4b-87e7-4521a5f783b8","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:55:39.390Z","parentId":"25de4042-2e13-4580-a159-b8cfb2f15c0d"}
